<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="State_of_Israel">State of Israel</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Beersheba&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: State of Israel">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="1947-49_war">1947-49 war</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Beersheba&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: 1947-49 war">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Beersheba_(1948)" title="Battle of Beersheba (1948)">Battle of Beersheba (1948)</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:IsraelPhil.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/IsraelPhil.jpg/220px-IsraelPhil.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="148" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/IsraelPhil.jpg/330px-IsraelPhil.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/IsraelPhil.jpg/440px-IsraelPhil.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1400" data-file-height="942" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:IsraelPhil.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Israel Philharmonic Orchestra performing in Beersheba, Israel, 1948</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beersheba,_Monument_to_Negev_Brigade,_Bunker_02.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Beersheba%2C_Monument_to_Negev_Brigade%2C_Bunker_02.jpg/220px-Beersheba%2C_Monument_to_Negev_Brigade%2C_Bunker_02.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Beersheba%2C_Monument_to_Negev_Brigade%2C_Bunker_02.jpg/330px-Beersheba%2C_Monument_to_Negev_Brigade%2C_Bunker_02.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Beersheba%2C_Monument_to_Negev_Brigade%2C_Bunker_02.jpg/440px-Beersheba%2C_Monument_to_Negev_Brigade%2C_Bunker_02.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3072" data-file-height="2304" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beersheba,_Monument_to_Negev_Brigade,_Bunker_02.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Monument to the Negev Brigade, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danny_Karavan" class="mw-redirect" title="Danny Karavan">Danny Karavan</a></div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:%D7%A9%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%94_%D7%91.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/%D7%A9%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%94_%D7%91.PNG/220px-%D7%A9%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%94_%D7%91.PNG" decoding="async" width="220" height="153" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/%D7%A9%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%94_%D7%91.PNG/330px-%D7%A9%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%94_%D7%91.PNG 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/%D7%A9%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%94_%D7%91.PNG/440px-%D7%A9%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%94_%D7%91.PNG 2x" data-file-width="2001" data-file-height="1388" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:%D7%A9%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%94_%D7%91.PNG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Beersheba in the 1960s</div></div></div>
<p>In 1947, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Nations_Special_Committee_on_Palestine" title="United Nations Special Committee on Palestine">United Nations Special Committee on Palestine</a> (UNSCOP) proposed that Beersheba be included within the Jewish state in their partition plan for Palestine.<sup id="cite_ref-UNSCOP_39-0" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-UNSCOP-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup> However, when the UN's Ad Hoc Committee revised the plan, they moved Beersheva to the Arab state on account of it being primarily Arab.<sup id="cite_ref-UNSCOP_39-1" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-UNSCOP-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup> Egyptian forces had been stationed at Beersheva since May 1948.
</p><p>It was <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yigal_Allon" title="Yigal Allon">Yigal Allon</a> who proposed the conquest of Beersheba,<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup> which  was approved by Prime Minister <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Ben-Gurion" title="David Ben-Gurion">David Ben-Gurion</a>. According to Israeli historian <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benny_Morris" title="Benny Morris">Benny Morris</a>, he ordered the  "conquest of Beersheba, occupation of outposts around it, [and] demolition of most of the town."<sup id="cite_ref-Morris467_42-0" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-Morris467-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup> The objective was to break the Egyptian blockade of Israeli convoys to the Negev. The Egyptian army did not expect an offensive and fled en masse.<sup id="cite_ref-googleil_43-0" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-googleil-43">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup> Israel bombed the town on October 16,<sup id="cite_ref-Abu-Rabia_2_44-0" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-Abu-Rabia_2-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup> At 4:00&#160;am on October 21, the 8th Brigade's 89th <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battalion" title="Battalion">battalion</a> and the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negev_Brigade" title="Negev Brigade">Negev Brigade</a>'s 7th and 9th battalions moved in, some troops advancing from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mishmar_HaNegev" title="Mishmar HaNegev">Mishmar HaNegev</a> junction, 20 kilometres (12&#160;mi) north of Beersheba, others from the Turkish train station and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hatzerim" title="Hatzerim">Hatzerim</a>. By 9:45, Beersheba was in Israeli hands. Around 120 Egyptian soldiers were taken prisoner. All of the Arab inhabitants, who had resisted, were expelled <sup id="cite_ref-Reiter_17-1" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-Reiter-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> with the remaining Arab civilians, 200 men and 150 women and children, taken to the police fort and, on October 25, the women, children, disabled and elderly were driven by truck to the Gaza border. The Egyptian soldiers were interned in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/POW" class="mw-redirect" title="POW">POW</a> camps. Some men lived in the local mosque and were put to work cleaning but when it was discovered that they were supplying information to the Egyptian army they were also deported.<sup id="cite_ref-Morris467_42-1" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-Morris467-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup> The town was subject to large-scale looting by the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haganah" title="Haganah">Haganah</a>, and by December, in one calculation, the total number of Arabs driven out from Beersheva and surrounding areas reached 30,000 with many ending up in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jordan" title="Jordan">Jordan</a> as refugees.<sup id="cite_ref-Abu-Rabia_2_44-1" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-Abu-Rabia_2-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> Following <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_Yoav" title="Operation Yoav">Operation Yoav</a>, a 10-kilometer radius exclusion zone around Beersheba was enforced into which no Bedouin were allowed.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup> In response, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Nations_Security_Council" title="United Nations Security Council">United Nations Security Council</a> passed two resolutions on the 4th and 16 November demanding that Israel withdraw from the area.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-47">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="First_four_decades">First four decades</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Beersheba&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: First four decades">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>Following the conclusion of the war, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1949_Armistice_Agreements" title="1949 Armistice Agreements">1949 Armistice Agreements</a> formally granted Beersheba to Israel. The town was then transformed into an Israeli city with only an exiguous Arab minority.<sup id="cite_ref-Reiter_17-2" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-Reiter-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> Beersheba was deemed strategically important due to its location with a reliable water supply and at a major crossroads, northwest to Hebron and <a href="Jerusalem" title="Jerusalem">Jerusalem</a>, east to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dead_Sea" title="Dead Sea">Dead Sea</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Karak" class="mw-redirect" title="Al Karak">al Karak</a>, south to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aqaba" title="Aqaba">Aqaba</a>, west to Gaza and southwest to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auja_al-Hafir" title="Auja al-Hafir">Al-Auja</a> and the border with <a href="../../bit.ly/2gTO313" title="Egypt">Egypt</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-googleil_43-1" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-googleil-43">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>After a few months, the town's war-damaged houses were repaired. As a post-independence wave of Jewish immigration to Israel began, Beersheba experienced a population boom as thousands of immigrants moved in. The city rapidly expanded beyond its core, which became known as the "Old City," as new neighborhoods were built around it, complete with various housing projects such as apartment buildings and houses with auxiliary farms, as well as shopping centers and schools. The Old City was turned into a city center, with shops, restaurants, and government and utility offices. An industrial area and one of the largest cinemas in Israel were also built in the city. By 1956, Beersheba was a booming city of 22,000.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-48">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-49">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup> In 1959, during <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wadi_Salib_riots" title="Wadi Salib riots">Wadi Salib riots</a>, riots spread quickly to other parts of the country, including Beersheba.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-50">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soroka_Medical_Center" title="Soroka Medical Center">Soroka Hospital</a> opened its doors in 1960. By 1968, the population had grown to 80,000.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup> The University of the Negev, which would later become Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, was established in 1969. The then <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Presidents_of_Egypt" class="mw-redirect" title="List of Presidents of Egypt">Egyptian president</a> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anwar_Sadat" title="Anwar Sadat">Anwar Sadat</a> visited Beersheba in 1979. In 1983, its population was more than 110,000.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Latest_urban_development">Latest urban development</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Beersheba&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Latest urban development">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:%D7%9E%D7%91%D7%98_%D7%A2%D7%9C_%D7%94%D7%A2%D7%99%D7%A8_%D7%91%D7%90%D7%A8_%D7%A9%D7%91%D7%A2,_%D7%90%D7%9E%D7%A6%D7%A2_%D7%A9%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA_%D7%94%D7%A9%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%99%D7%9D.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/%D7%9E%D7%91%D7%98_%D7%A2%D7%9C_%D7%94%D7%A2%D7%99%D7%A8_%D7%91%D7%90%D7%A8_%D7%A9%D7%91%D7%A2%2C_%D7%90%D7%9E%D7%A6%D7%A2_%D7%A9%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA_%D7%94%D7%A9%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%99%D7%9D.JPG/250px-%D7%9E%D7%91%D7%98_%D7%A2%D7%9C_%D7%94%D7%A2%D7%99%D7%A8_%D7%91%D7%90%D7%A8_%D7%A9%D7%91%D7%A2%2C_%D7%90%D7%9E%D7%A6%D7%A2_%D7%A9%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA_%D7%94%D7%A9%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%99%D7%9D.JPG" decoding="async" width="250" height="117" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/%D7%9E%D7%91%D7%98_%D7%A2%D7%9C_%D7%94%D7%A2%D7%99%D7%A8_%D7%91%D7%90%D7%A8_%D7%A9%D7%91%D7%A2%2C_%D7%90%D7%9E%D7%A6%D7%A2_%D7%A9%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA_%D7%94%D7%A9%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%99%D7%9D.JPG/375px-%D7%9E%D7%91%D7%98_%D7%A2%D7%9C_%D7%94%D7%A2%D7%99%D7%A8_%D7%91%D7%90%D7%A8_%D7%A9%D7%91%D7%A2%2C_%D7%90%D7%9E%D7%A6%D7%A2_%D7%A9%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA_%D7%94%D7%A9%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%99%D7%9D.JPG 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/%D7%9E%D7%91%D7%98_%D7%A2%D7%9C_%D7%94%D7%A2%D7%99%D7%A8_%D7%91%D7%90%D7%A8_%D7%A9%D7%91%D7%A2%2C_%D7%90%D7%9E%D7%A6%D7%A2_%D7%A9%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA_%D7%94%D7%A9%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%99%D7%9D.JPG/500px-%D7%9E%D7%91%D7%98_%D7%A2%D7%9C_%D7%94%D7%A2%D7%99%D7%A8_%D7%91%D7%90%D7%A8_%D7%A9%D7%91%D7%A2%2C_%D7%90%D7%9E%D7%A6%D7%A2_%D7%A9%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA_%D7%94%D7%A9%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%99%D7%9D.JPG 2x" data-file-width="3681" data-file-height="1723" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:%D7%9E%D7%91%D7%98_%D7%A2%D7%9C_%D7%94%D7%A2%D7%99%D7%A8_%D7%91%D7%90%D7%A8_%D7%A9%D7%91%D7%A2,_%D7%90%D7%9E%D7%A6%D7%A2_%D7%A9%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA_%D7%94%D7%A9%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%99%D7%9D.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Beersheba in the mid-1980s</div></div></div>
<p>As part of its <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blueprint_Negev" title="Blueprint Negev">Blueprint Negev</a> project, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jewish_National_Fund" title="Jewish National Fund">Jewish National Fund</a> is funding major redevelopment projects in Beersheba. One project is the Beersheba River Walk, a 900-acre (3.6-square-kilometre) riverfront district with green spaces, hiking trails, a 3,000-seat sports hall, a 15-acre (6.1-hectare) boating lake filled with recycled waste water, promenades, restaurants, cafés, galleries, boat rentals, a 12,000-seat amphitheater, playgrounds, and a bridge along the route of the city's <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mekorot" title="Mekorot">Mekorot</a> water pipes. The plans include building new homes overlooking the park and neighborhood.<sup id="cite_ref-park_52-0" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-park-52">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup> At the official entrance to the river park will be the Beit Eshel Park, which will consist of a park built around a courtyard with historic remains from the settlement of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beit_Eshel" title="Beit Eshel">Beit Eshel</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-blueprint_53-0" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-blueprint-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beer_Sheva_Aerial_View.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Beer_Sheva_Aerial_View.jpg/250px-Beer_Sheva_Aerial_View.jpg" decoding="async" width="250" height="112" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Beer_Sheva_Aerial_View.jpg/375px-Beer_Sheva_Aerial_View.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Beer_Sheva_Aerial_View.jpg/500px-Beer_Sheva_Aerial_View.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5312" data-file-height="2376" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beer_Sheva_Aerial_View.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Panorama of Beersheba</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:PipesBridge.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/PipesBridge.jpg/220px-PipesBridge.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/PipesBridge.jpg/330px-PipesBridge.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/PipesBridge.jpg/440px-PipesBridge.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4608" data-file-height="3072" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:PipesBridge.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Pipes Bridge, 2012</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beer_Sheba_Israel_IMG_6789.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Beer_Sheba_Israel_IMG_6789.JPG/220px-Beer_Sheba_Israel_IMG_6789.JPG" decoding="async" width="220" height="210" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Beer_Sheba_Israel_IMG_6789.JPG/330px-Beer_Sheba_Israel_IMG_6789.JPG 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Beer_Sheba_Israel_IMG_6789.JPG/440px-Beer_Sheba_Israel_IMG_6789.JPG 2x" data-file-width="1432" data-file-height="1367" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beer_Sheba_Israel_IMG_6789.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Modern Beersheba</div></div></div>
<p>Four new shopping malls are planned.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The time period mentioned near this tag is ambiguous. (August 2019)">when?</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> The first, Kanyon Beersheba, will be a 115,000-square-metre (1,240,000-square-foot) ecologically planned mall with pools for collecting rainwater and lighting generated by solar panels on the roof. It will be situated next to an 8,000-meter park with bicycle paths.<sup id="cite_ref-blueprint_53-1" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-blueprint-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-54">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-55">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup> Another mall will be a farmer's market, the first ever in Israel. It will be an enclosed, circular complex with 400 spaces for vendors, and it will be surrounded by parks and greenery.<sup id="cite_ref-blueprint_53-2" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-blueprint-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>A new central bus station was built in the city. The station has a glass-enclosed complex also containing shops and cafés.<sup id="cite_ref-blueprint_53-3" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-blueprint-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In recent years,<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The time period mentioned near this tag is ambiguous. (August 2019)">when?</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> some $10.5&#160;million has been invested in renovating Beersheba's Old City, preserving historical buildings and upgrading infrastructure.<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-56">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup> The Turkish Quarter is also being redeveloped with newly cobbled streets, widened sidewalks, and the restoration of Turkish homes into areas for dining and shopping.<sup id="cite_ref-park_52-1" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-park-52">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2011, city hall announced plans to turn Beersheba into the "water city" of Israel.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-57">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup> One of the projects, "Beersheva beach," envisions a 7-<a href="Dunam#Syria,_Israel,_Palestine,_Jordan,_Lebanon_and_Turkey" title="Dunam">dunam</a> facility opposite city hall.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-58">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-59">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup> Other projects include new fountains near the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soroka_Medical_Center" title="Soroka Medical Center">Soroka Medical Center</a> and in front of the Shamoon College of Engineering.
</p><p>In the 1990s, as skyscrapers began to appear in Israel, the construction of high-rise buildings began in Beersheba.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-60">&#91;60&#93;</a></sup> Today, downtown Beersheba has been described as a "clean, compact, and somewhat sterile-looking collection of high-rise office and residential towers."<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-61">&#91;61&#93;</a></sup> The city's tallest building is Rambam Square 2, a 32-story apartment building.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-62">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup> Many additional high-rise buildings are planned or are under construction, including skyscrapers.<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-63">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-64">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-65">&#91;65&#93;</a></sup> There are further plans to build luxury residential towers in the city.<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-66">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The city is undergoing a major construction boom,<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The time period mentioned near this tag is ambiguous. (August 2019)">when?</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> which includes both development of urban design elements, such as water fountains and bridges, and environmental development such as playgrounds and parks.<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-67">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In December 2012, a plan to build 16,000 new housing units in the Ramot Gimel neighborhood was scrapped in favor of creating a new <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urban_forest" title="Urban forest">urban forest</a>, which will span 1,360 acres (550&#160;ha) and serve as the area's "green lung", as part of the plans to develop a "green band" around the city. The forest will include designated picnic areas, biking trails, and walking trails. According to Mayor <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruvik_Danilovich" title="Ruvik Danilovich">Ruvik Danilovich</a>, Beersheba still has an abundance of open, underdeveloped spaces that can be used for urban development.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-68">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2017, a new urban building plan was approved for the city, designed to raise the city's population to 340,000 by 2030. Under the plan, 13,000 more housing units will be built, along with industrial and business developments occupying a total of four million square meters. A second public hospital is also planned.<sup id="cite_ref-globes_69-0" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-globes-69">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Security_incidents_in_the_city">Security incidents in the city</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Beersheba&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Security incidents in the city">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On October 19, 1998, sixty four people were wounded in a grenade attack.<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-70">&#91;70&#93;</a></sup> 
On August 31, 2004, sixteen people were killed in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beersheba_bus_bombings" title="Beersheba bus bombings">two suicide bombings on commuter buses</a> in Beersheba for which <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamas" title="Hamas">Hamas</a> claimed responsibility. On August 28, 2005, another suicide bomber attacked the central bus station, seriously injuring two security guards and 45 bystanders.<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-71">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup> During <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaza_War_(2008%E2%80%9309)" class="mw-redirect" title="Gaza War (2008–09)">Operation Cast Lead</a>, which began on December 27, 2008 and lasted until the ceasefire on January 18, 2009, Hamas fired 2,378 rockets (such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BM-21_Grad" title="BM-21 Grad">Grad</a> rockets) and mortars, from Gaza into southern Israel, including Beersheba. The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Palestinian_rocket_attacks_on_Israel" class="mw-redirect" title="List of Palestinian rocket attacks on Israel">rocket attacks have continued</a>, but have been only partially effective since the introduction of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_Dome" title="Iron Dome">Iron Dome</a> rocket defense system.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-72">&#91;72&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-73">&#91;73&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-74">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-75">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2010 an Arab attacked and injured two people with an axe.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-76">&#91;76&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-77">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-78">&#91;78&#93;</a></sup> In 2012, a Palestinian from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jenin" title="Jenin">Jenin</a> was stopped before a stabbing attack in a "safe house."<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-79">&#91;79&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-80">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup> On October 18, 2015, a lone gunman <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beersheva_bus_station_shooting" title="Beersheva bus station shooting">shot and killed</a> a soldier guarding the Beersheva bus station before being gunned down by police.<sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-81">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup> In September 2016, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shin_Bet" title="Shin Bet">Shin Bet</a> thwarted a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palestinian_Islamic_Jihad" class="mw-redirect" title="Palestinian Islamic Jihad">Palestinian Islamic Jihad</a> terror attack at a wedding hall in Beersheba.<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-82">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-83">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Emblem_of_Beersheba">Emblem of Beersheba</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Beersheba&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Emblem of Beersheba">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:82px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beer_Sheva_COA_stamp_1965.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Beer_Sheva_COA_stamp_1965.png/80px-Beer_Sheva_COA_stamp_1965.png" decoding="async" width="80" height="153" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Beer_Sheva_COA_stamp_1965.png/120px-Beer_Sheva_COA_stamp_1965.png 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Beer_Sheva_COA_stamp_1965.png/160px-Beer_Sheva_COA_stamp_1965.png 2x" data-file-width="390" data-file-height="746" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beer_Sheva_COA_stamp_1965.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Beersheva emblem on a 1965 stamp</div></div></div>
<p>Since 1950, Beersheba has changed its municipal emblem several times. 
The 1950 emblem, designed by Abraham Khalili, featured a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamarix" title="Tamarix">tamarix</a> tree, a factory and water flowing from a pipeline.<sup id="cite_ref-city_sign_84-0" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-city_sign-84">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup> In 1972 the emblem was modernized with the symbolic representation of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twelve_Tribes" class="mw-redirect" title="Twelve Tribes">Twelve Tribes</a> and a tower.<sup id="cite_ref-city_sign_84-1" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-city_sign-84">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup> Words from the Bible are inscribed: Abraham "planted a tamarix tree in Beersheba." (Genesis 21:33) Since 2012, it has incorporated the number seven as part of the city rebranding.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Geography">Geography</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Beersheba&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Geography">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:NahalashanS.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/NahalashanS.jpg/220px-NahalashanS.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="144" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/NahalashanS.jpg/330px-NahalashanS.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/NahalashanS.jpg/440px-NahalashanS.jpg 2x" data-file-width="750" data-file-height="490" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:NahalashanS.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Dry riverbed in Nahal Ashan park</div></div></div>
<p>Beersheba is located on the northern edge of the Negev desert 115 kilometres (71&#160;mi) south-east of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tel_Aviv" title="Tel Aviv">Tel Aviv</a> and 120 kilometres (75&#160;mi) south-west of Jerusalem. The city is located on the main route from the center and north of the country to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eilat" title="Eilat">Eilat</a> in the far south. The Beersheba Valley has been populated for thousands of years, as it has available water, which flows from the Hebron hills in the winter and is stored underground in vast quantities.<sup id="cite_ref-geog_85-0" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-geog-85">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup> The main river in Beersheba is <i>Nahal Beersheva</i>, a <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wadi" title="Wadi">wadi</a></i> that floods in the winter. The Kovshim and Katef streams are other important wadis that pass through the city. Beersheba is surrounded by a number of satellite towns, including <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omer,_Israel" title="Omer, Israel">Omer</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lehavim" title="Lehavim">Lehavim</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meitar" title="Meitar">Meitar</a>, and the Bedouin localities of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rahat" title="Rahat">Rahat</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tel_as-Sabi" class="mw-redirect" title="Tel as-Sabi">Tel as-Sabi</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakiya" title="Lakiya">Lakiya</a>.
Just north west of the city (near Ramot neighborhood ) is a region called Goral hills (heb:גבעות גורל lit: hills of fate), the area has hills with up to 500 metres (1,600 feet) <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Above_sea_level" class="mw-redirect" title="Above sea level">above sea level</a> and low as 300 metres (980 feet)  above sea level.<sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-86">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup> Due to heavy construction the flora unique to the area is endangered.
North east of the city (north to the Neve Menahem neighborhood) there are <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loess" title="Loess">Loess</a> plains and dry river bands.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Climate">Climate</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Beersheba&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Climate">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Beersheba has a hot <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desert_climate" title="Desert climate">desert climate</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification" title="Köppen climate classification">Köppen climate classification</a> <i>BWh</i>) with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mediterranean_climate" title="Mediterranean climate">Mediterranean</a> influences. The city has both characteristics of Mediterranean and desert climates. Summers are hot and dry, and winters are mild. Rainfall is highly concentrated in the winter season, even more so than other cities with a similar climate such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almer%C3%ADa" title="Almería">Almería</a> in southern Spain. In summer, the temperatures are high in daytime and nighttime with an average high of 34.7&#160;°C (94&#160;°F) and an average low of 21.4&#160;°C (71&#160;°F). Winters have an average high of 17.7&#160;°C (64&#160;°F) and average low of 7.1&#160;°C (45&#160;°F). Snow is very rare; a snowfall on February 20, 2015 was the first such occurrence in the city since 1992.<sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="Beersheba#cite_note-87">&#91;87&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Precipitation in summer is rare, the most rainfalls come in winter between September to May, but the annual amount is low, averaging 195.1 millimeters (7.7&#160;in) per year. Sandstorms, haze and fog are common, especially in winter, as a result of the high humidity.
</p>
